Having students create their own podcasts ✨

1. We listen to models of podcasts and take notes 
2. Brainstorm their podcast as a whole and the genre they want. 
3. We go over copyright laws and fair use. 
4. They create their notes for episode one
5. Students create their cover art.
6. We then create on anchor.fm (I create their accounts so I have access)
7. They get creating! I sometimes even throw in ads that they can record and show what working with a brand would be like! 

Drop questions below 👇🏼

Merry Christmas ig fam ✨

Hoping everyone had a wonderful break away from all the crazy. I for one will admit I enjoyed all the snuggles, cuddles and vacation. Highly suggest turning your brain off of anything to do with teaching over a break if you can. Actually feeling ready to go back. ✨

Today was definitely a roll with the punches day. 

No electricity. PE subs never showed up. No technology. No bells. Student dismissal in a complete different area than where it typically is due to construction. 

A day filled with spur of the moment decisions. However? We ended up having so much fun. We got to read 3 chapters of our read aloud outside in the warm sunshine. Played a fun game outside. Did math in a small group on the ground with whiteboards. I thought of a last minute fun science with flashlights and highlighters and ended the day with some “PE” outside. 

Was it the day I originally planned? No. But students still learned so much and we had a lot of of fun. It really made me think about how amazing and flexible teachers are. If any of these things were to have happened in the corporate world, I’m pretty sure the day would’ve just been a work from home day. With literally nothing but the books and resources in my room we created fun, interactive lessons and got through all subjects. All this to share that wow we do more than a lot of jobs ask. That’s all. Hope your Monday wasn’t as “Monday” as mine.

A few things I have incorporated this year that have really helped with work/life balance. I love my job and honestly rarely have the Sunday Scaries this year and I believe a lot of it has to do with these below things.

1. Staying later two days a week. (Only 45 mins past contract time honestly so barely late) 
2. Leaving at contract time whenever possible. 
3. Prepping/making copies for the whole next week on Wednesday’s (our short day)  so my week goes Wednesday-Wednesday 
4. Exercising every day. If I’m not on my cycling bike I am going on a walk or riding bikes on the beach. 
5. Self grading and reflection is put on my students. They grade homework, quizzes, assignments and reflect on WHY they got them wrong. 
6. Packing a lunch and a snack and ACTUALLY eating said items. 
7. Running small groups has been a game changer in math. Less grading and tests and I honestly know where each of my students are in everything without having to really data track.

Interactive line plots ✨

What’s better than creating a giant one on the ground? I swear that always makes the kids more excited than doing a page out of the workbook any time.

1. Use masking tape to make a line 
2. Have students label with index cards. 
3. Have them apply an X to represent number of times repeated. 
4. Add a label, and snap a picture into their google slide as evidence 

You can find this in my TPT by searching: line plot activity ✨

Capture the flag house game ✨ 

We used this to prepare for our math state testing. I printed out questions and students had to work as a team to get the correct answer. They would check with me and each right answer earned them one steal. 

To promote team work I gave extra flags to cooperating and collaborative groups. The best part is each color represents different point values and they don’t get to find out until the end! 

I recommend making sure you discuss friendly competition first. We talked about how to support each other, not take people down. 

Got this idea from @thattrendyteacher_

#collaboration #classgames #reviewgames #teacher #teachersfollowteachers

Another review game for you ✨ 

Comment class game for a dm of this free resource 🤍

This one is called deal or no deal. All you need is 24 suitcases and rewards on the back. I like to tie this either to a worksheet  or a question deck to add engagement. 

Students get into teams and then select a suitcase number. This gets locked in under their name and cannot be changed. Students then answer a question and write it on a mini whiteboard. The first team who gets it correct gets to choose which number we check for the reward. Once we read it off, I cross it off from the list so the students can see what rewards are left, and the probability of it being the one they chose in the beginning. 

My rules for these types of games is everyone solves, teams always share and explain how they get an answer and teamwork is always rewarded. 

I love this because all teams end with some type of reward. We use house points in my class so the points just go towards their house. This idea originally came from @miss5th 

#classgame #teacher #teachersfollowteachers #reviewgame #endofyear #easyengagement #elementarymath #elementaryschool

End of the year projects with minimal prep >

✨comment 3act for a dm of this free resource 

I call these the 3-act lesson projects and the best part is you can do this for any grade level. I allow partners or groups to choose a grade level topic on the g fletchy website and they must work together to teach, present and asses the class on their topic. 

I give them a planning page and have them lay out what materials, supplies and technology they need. I even have them include a mini lesson of the topic covered to recap and review what we did this year. After the 3 act task, I have them give out some type of assessment like a kahoot or exit ticket. 

Best part? They’re doing all the planning, prep and teaching and you are just there to support. Comment below if you have any questions.

#endofyear #noprepactivities #elementaryschool #teacherlesson #teacher #teachersfollowteachers

I had to pack up my room because I am switching rooms but super lucky that I will be teaching at the same school this year. First week of school games✨

Get to know you Jenga is one of my favorites because it is so easy and can be adapted for any grade level. I got these jengas frlom dollar tree and color the ends different colors. They are placed on students desks and they play as a table group. A student will pull a Jenga and then answer a question about themselves from the list on our slideshow. ✨

Super easy and a way for students to learn more about the students in their class without having to stand up and share in front of everyone! 

#teachersfollowteachers #backtoschool #firstweekofschool  #primaryteacher #uppergradeteacher

My absolute favorite community game ✨

Floor is lava is played with sticky notes, a few groups of students, clipboard and paper key of routes. 

Students have to work together to make it across safely to the other side with the help of their lovely leader. The only thing they are allowed to say yes or no. If the student steps on the wrong path they just go to the back of the line. Once everyone is across I have them switch the leader to someone new and love to another route. 

You can find this in my TPT or link in bio ✨
